english:
  title: Three Kings
  author: Lee Je-hyeon
  language: eng
  text: |-
    Yu in ancient days faced the great flood—
    all under heaven drowned in chaos.
    The people suffered the poisoned waters,
    knowing not where to turn.
    Had Yu not mastered what was broken,
    we would have become fish.
    Three times he passed his own house
    without entering, though his son cried within.
    The people's struggle was his worry,
    and his own cracked hands brought no complaint.
    He dug the channels, let the waters flow,
    and the nine regions became solid earth.
    The people have not forgotten his grace—
    why speak merely of ten thousand years?
    The sage once said these words,
    and I harbor no doubt.

    Tang—
    O mighty Heaven's will made manifest!
    Yin rose to glory through your reign.
    You sought the worthy in humble fields,
    learned from them, and made them ministers.
    With net spread open on three sides,
    all the world turned toward benevolence.
    You served Heaven with joy unfeigned,
    and destroyed the tyrant Jie with the people's consent.
    Without revealing your virtue,
    how could the people have given trust?
    This sacred teaching stands:
    "Each day renew yourself, and renew again."

    Wen Wang—
    The Zhou accumulated merit
    since the days of Hou Ji.
    When the Western Earl rose and flourished,
    he became the model for four realms.
    The worthy came forth to serve,
    and disputes were justly resolved.
    He unfolded the symbols of the I Ching,
    and brought forth songs of praise.
    With only two-thirds of the land in hand,
    yet served the Shang without failing in duty.
    Is this not the very essence of culture?
    His virtue reached its pinnacle.
  footnotes:
    - Yu the Great (禹) is legendary for spending thirteen years controlling the Great Flood, working so tirelessly that he passed his own home three times without entering to see his newborn son.
    - Tang (湯) was the founder of the Shang Dynasty, known for his benevolence and for overthrowing the tyrannical Xia ruler Jie.
    - Wen Wang (文王) was the father of the founder of the Zhou Dynasty. Though he ruled only two-thirds of the land, he maintained loyalty to the declining Shang, exemplifying virtue.
    - The phrase 'Each day renew yourself, and renew again' comes from the I Ching and reflects the Confucian emphasis on continuous moral self-cultivation.
